# Supabase — Foreign Data Wrappers (FDW) Reference

Foreign Data Wrappers let you query external services — Stripe, Firebase, S3, BigQuery,
Airtable, Redis — as if they were regular Postgres tables. One SQL query can JOIN your
own data with live data from any external source.

---

## Critical Security Rule

> FDW foreign tables MUST always be in a `private` schema — NEVER in `public`.
> Foreign tables bypass RLS. If you put them in public, anyone with your anon key
> can SELECT from Stripe, Firebase, or wherever you connected.

```sql
CREATE SCHEMA IF NOT EXISTS private;
-- All foreign tables go here — not in public
```

---

## Enable the Wrappers Extension

```sql
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS wrappers WITH SCHEMA extensions;
```

---

## Stripe FDW — Query Stripe Data as SQL Tables

Use case: JOIN your orders table with live Stripe subscription data, audit billing,
check customer status, build admin dashboards without API calls.

### Setup
```sql
-- 1. Store Stripe secret key in Vault (never hardcode)
SELECT vault.create_secret('sk_live_...', 'stripe_secret_key', 'Stripe live secret key');
-- Copy the returned UUID

-- 2. Create the Stripe foreign server
CREATE SERVER stripe_server
  FOREIGN DATA WRAPPER stripe_wrapper
  OPTIONS (
    api_key_id '[VAULT_SECRET_UUID]'  -- UUID from vault.create_secret above
  );

-- 3. Create a schema for Stripe tables (private — never public)
CREATE SCHEMA IF NOT EXISTS stripe;
REVOKE ALL ON SCHEMA stripe FROM PUBLIC, anon, authenticated;

-- 4. Create foreign tables (only create the ones you need)
CREATE FOREIGN TABLE stripe.customers (
  id TEXT,
  email TEXT,
  name TEXT,
  created TIMESTAMP,
  attrs JSONB
)
SERVER stripe_server
OPTIONS (object 'customers', rowid_column 'id');

CREATE FOREIGN TABLE stripe.subscriptions (
  id TEXT,
  customer TEXT,
  status TEXT,
  current_period_start TIMESTAMP,
  current_period_end TIMESTAMP,
  attrs JSONB
)
SERVER stripe_server
OPTIONS (object 'subscriptions', rowid_column 'id');

CREATE FOREIGN TABLE stripe.invoices (
  id TEXT,
  customer TEXT,
  status TEXT,
  amount_due INTEGER,
  amount_paid INTEGER,
  created TIMESTAMP,
  attrs JSONB
)
SERVER stripe_server
OPTIONS (object 'invoices', rowid_column 'id');
```

### Query examples
```sql
-- JOIN your profiles table with live Stripe subscription status
SELECT
  p.id,
  p.email,
  s.status AS stripe_status,
  s.current_period_end AS renews_at
FROM public.profiles p
LEFT JOIN stripe.subscriptions s ON s.customer = p.stripe_customer_id
WHERE s.status = 'active';

-- Find customers whose subscription expired but still have active access in your DB
SELECT p.email, p.stripe_customer_id, s.status
FROM public.profiles p
JOIN stripe.subscriptions s ON s.customer = p.stripe_customer_id
WHERE s.status = 'canceled'
  AND p.subscription_active = true;  -- data mismatch — fix these

-- Audit: invoices not linked to any profile
SELECT i.id, i.customer, i.amount_due
FROM stripe.invoices i
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
  SELECT 1 FROM public.profiles p WHERE p.stripe_customer_id = i.customer
);
```

### Access from server-side Next.js (via DB function)
```sql
-- Create a function so server-side code can call it via .rpc()
-- Direct SELECT on stripe.* schema is only available to service_role
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_user_stripe_status(p_user_id UUID)
RETURNS TABLE(stripe_status TEXT, renews_at TIMESTAMP)
LANGUAGE sql SECURITY DEFINER
SET search_path = public, stripe AS $$
  SELECT s.status, s.current_period_end
  FROM stripe.subscriptions s
  JOIN public.profiles p ON p.stripe_customer_id = s.customer
  WHERE p.id = p_user_id
  LIMIT 1;
$$;
```

```typescript
// app/api/subscription/route.ts
const { data } = await supabase.rpc('get_user_stripe_status', { p_user_id: user.id })
```

